WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.721 --> 00:00:14.556
I'm wearing crampons.

2
00:00:21.522 --> 00:00:25.150
I'm in Sicily on Mount Etna.

3
00:00:27.444 --> 00:00:30.906
That's the sea. where it's warm and sunny.

4
00:00:32.407 --> 00:00:34.826
This is the mountain.

5
00:00:34.910 --> 00:00:37.287
where it's sunny. but not warm.

6
00:00:37.371 --> 00:00:40.415
That is the top of the mountain
that is an active volcano.

7
00:00:42.584 --> 00:00:44.127
Contrasts.

8
00:00:47.130 --> 00:00:48.924
That's what it's all about.

9
00:00:57.724 --> 00:01:00.602
<i>Sicily is. of course. Italian.</i>

10
00:01:00.686 --> 00:01:04.481
<i>but at the same time.</i>
<i>unapologetically itself.</i>

11
00:01:04.564 --> 00:01:07.526
<i>Italy's largest island</i>
<i>sits just off the toe of the boot</i>

12
00:01:07.609 --> 00:01:09.528
<i>at the crossroads of the Mediterranean.</i>

13
00:01:12.906 --> 00:01:14.658
<i>It's a place of contradictions.</i>

14
00:01:14.741 --> 00:01:18.495
<i>famous for its dazzling beaches</i>
<i>and archaeological treasures.</i>

15
00:01:18.579 --> 00:01:21.873
<i>but infamous for the shadow</i>
<i>cast by criminality</i>

16
00:01:21.957 --> 00:01:23.125
<i>and corruption.</i>

17
00:01:24.626 --> 00:01:26.712
<i>These contrasts are very evident</i>

18
00:01:26.795 --> 00:01:30.048
<i>in the culture of the people here</i>
<i>and in the food they eat.</i>

19
00:01:33.677 --> 00:01:35.554
<i>I'm starting my journey in the shadow</i>

20
00:01:35.637 --> 00:01:38.307
<i>of Sicily's most notorious</i>
<i>geological threat.</i>

21
00:01:38.390 --> 00:01:41.685
<i>Mount Etna. where. ironically.</i>

22
00:01:41.768 --> 00:01:44.896
<i>one of the island's</i>
<i>most prized products thrives.</i>

23
00:01:46.690 --> 00:01:48.358
<i>When I was a kid. I don't ever remember</i>

24
00:01:48.442 --> 00:01:50.986
having a blood orange in America.

25
00:01:51.069 --> 00:01:54.614
But when we moved to Florence.
the grocer had them.

26
00:01:54.698 --> 00:01:56.491
<i>I had never seen anything like it.</i>

27
00:01:57.492 --> 00:01:59.661
<i>It's absolutely delicious.</i>

28
00:01:59.745 --> 00:02:02.873
<i>And my kids go completely mad for them.</i>

29
00:02:03.540 --> 00:02:05.876
In fact. I gave them
a whole bunch the other day

30
00:02:05.959 --> 00:02:07.669
'cause I could tell their blood sugar

31
00:02:07.753 --> 00:02:10.339
was running a little low in the afternoon.

32
00:02:13.050 --> 00:02:14.926
<i>The best blood oranges are grown</i>

33
00:02:15.010 --> 00:02:18.180
<i>just inland of Sicily's</i>
<i>second city. Catania...</i>

34
00:02:19.723 --> 00:02:23.226
<i>where the snow of Etna meets</i>
<i>the warm sun of the plains.</i>

35
00:02:27.606 --> 00:02:29.566
-Good morning.
-Welcome.

36
00:02:29.650 --> 00:02:31.360
-Stanley.
-Gerardo.

37
00:02:32.152 --> 00:02:36.156
<i>These 60 hectares of oranges</i>
<i>belong to Gerardo Diana.</i>

38
00:02:38.325 --> 00:02:40.369
Your family has had this
for how many generations?

39
00:02:40.452 --> 00:02:41.953
-For forever.
-Like five genera-- yeah.

40
00:02:42.037 --> 00:02:44.289
Basically. whenever there is
the history of the family.

41
00:02:44.373 --> 00:02:45.540
there is always the history

42
00:02:45.624 --> 00:02:46.667
-of this farm.
-Right.

43
00:02:46.750 --> 00:02:48.335
It's a lot of work.

44
00:02:48.418 --> 00:02:49.795
but it's beautiful work.

45
00:02:50.671 --> 00:02:52.047
This year. it's a good season.

46
00:02:52.130 --> 00:02:53.924
- Is it?
- We have a lot of fruit.

47
00:02:55.133 --> 00:02:58.095
<i>The blood orange</i>
<i>isn't easy to cultivate.</i>

48
00:02:58.178 --> 00:03:01.223
<i>but it grows here thanks</i>
<i>to the dynamic microclimate</i>

49
00:03:01.306 --> 00:03:03.392
<i>created by the volcano.</i>

50
00:03:03.475 --> 00:03:07.145
Right now. it's January.
and it's beautiful weather here.

51
00:03:07.229 --> 00:03:09.481
But you get these fluctuations
in temperature. right?

52
00:03:09.564 --> 00:03:11.483
-Every day.
-Every day?

53
00:03:11.566 --> 00:03:13.860
Basically. now we'll reach the 20 degrees.

54
00:03:13.944 --> 00:03:15.612
-Uh-huh?
-And tomorrow morning.

55
00:03:15.696 --> 00:03:17.698
thanks to Mount Etna microclimate...

56
00:03:17.781 --> 00:03:19.408
-Yeah.
-...we have zero degrees.

57
00:03:19.491 --> 00:03:22.411
This is what it makes
our blood orange special.

58
00:03:22.494 --> 00:03:23.578
I see.

59
00:03:23.662 --> 00:03:25.622
They have inside some substances.

60
00:03:25.705 --> 00:03:27.582
which are very difficult for me
to say in English

61
00:03:27.666 --> 00:03:29.251
-because they-- <i>anthocyanins.</i>
-So. just say them in Italian.

62
00:03:29.334 --> 00:03:30.419
Anthocyanins.

63
00:03:30.502 --> 00:03:31.586
In Italian. what is it?

64
00:03:31.670 --> 00:03:32.754
Anthocyanins.

65
00:03:32.838 --> 00:03:35.257
-Mm-hmm.
-It's basically they react

66
00:03:35.340 --> 00:03:38.468
to the different-- to this. uh.
difference of temperature.

67
00:03:38.552 --> 00:03:39.928
-Yeah.
-And they become.

68
00:03:40.011 --> 00:03:42.055
-in order to protect itself...
-Yeah.

69
00:03:42.139 --> 00:03:43.765
...all the fruit. it becomes all red.

70
00:03:43.849 --> 00:03:45.725
Yes. I've--
I've read about this.

71
00:03:45.809 --> 00:03:47.436
They're high in antioxidants.

72
00:03:47.519 --> 00:03:49.187
- Exactly.
- Right? High in vitamin C.

73
00:03:49.271 --> 00:03:52.941
And this is really one of those
good effects of Mount Etna.

74
00:03:57.112 --> 00:03:59.531
<i>On a good morning.</i>
<i>Gerardo and the pickers</i>

75
00:03:59.614 --> 00:04:03.201
<i>can harvest up to</i>
<i>800 kilograms each of oranges.</i>

76
00:04:03.285 --> 00:04:05.120
<i>some of which become lunch.</i>

77
00:04:09.624 --> 00:04:11.042
<i>Salute. Salute.</i>

78
00:04:11.126 --> 00:04:12.127
Cheers.

79
00:04:16.256 --> 00:04:18.884
Do you eat this every day?
Or almost every day?

80
00:04:18.967 --> 00:04:20.677
Every day.

81
00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:21.845
<i>Si. Si.</i>

82
00:04:22.304 --> 00:04:24.014
-Can I cut one open?
-Yeah. you should.

83
00:04:28.101 --> 00:04:29.311
Oh. my God.

84
00:04:29.394 --> 00:04:30.854
- Look at that.
- What a nice color.

85
00:04:30.937 --> 00:04:32.397
-Look at that.
-Incredible.

86
00:04:32.481 --> 00:04:34.316
And it's very good because it has a lot

87
00:04:34.399 --> 00:04:36.193
- of mineral salts inside.
- Yeah.

88
00:04:37.194 --> 00:04:40.739
And then. we can go on working.
which. we won't be tired.

89
00:04:40.822 --> 00:04:42.240
- Right.
- Because if we would eat pasta.

90
00:04:42.324 --> 00:04:43.158
then it would be difficult

91
00:04:43.241 --> 00:04:44.868
-to go back and work. so.
-Yes. then you overdo it.

92
00:04:44.951 --> 00:04:46.119
You save that for-- for nighttime.

93
00:04:46.203 --> 00:04:47.537
-For the nighttime.
-For the nighttime.

94
00:04:49.206 --> 00:04:50.749
<i>The sweetness of the oranges</i>

95
00:04:50.832 --> 00:04:52.876
<i>is paired with fennel that grows wild</i>

96
00:04:52.959 --> 00:04:54.586
<i>on the outskirts of the farm.</i>

97
00:04:55.629 --> 00:04:59.174
The blood orange does not need...

98
00:04:59.633 --> 00:05:02.135
...help. because it has a great taste.

99
00:05:02.511 --> 00:05:04.179
But you can enrich it with
a bit of fennel.

100
00:05:04.262 --> 00:05:05.680
<i>Ãˆ buono.</i>

101
00:05:05.764 --> 00:05:07.724
Oh. my God. Oh yeah.

102
00:05:09.726 --> 00:05:12.229
It has a very strong flavor.

103
00:05:12.312 --> 00:05:14.648
which blends very good
with the red oranges.

104
00:05:14.731 --> 00:05:15.899
Because they're totally opposite.

105
00:05:15.982 --> 00:05:17.859
They're opposite. but they blend together.

106
00:05:17.943 --> 00:05:19.653
-It does-- it does work.
-It's like a wedding.

107
00:05:19.736 --> 00:05:21.404
Sometimes you need to be
different with your wife.

108
00:05:21.488 --> 00:05:22.989
Otherwise. it would be too monotonous.

109
00:05:23.073 --> 00:05:24.491
Yeah.

110
00:05:24.574 --> 00:05:25.575
Alright. should we eat?

111
00:05:29.871 --> 00:05:32.165
<i> Wedges of</i>
<i>freshly picked blood orange.</i>

112
00:05:32.249 --> 00:05:35.460
<i>sprigs of wild fennel.</i>
<i>splashes of olive oil.</i>

113
00:05:35.544 --> 00:05:38.213
<i>This is a mouthwatering</i>
<i>working man's lunch.</i>

114
00:05:40.966 --> 00:05:42.175
This is delicious.

115
00:05:43.176 --> 00:05:47.931
I can have fennel in London.
or America. or wherever.

116
00:05:48.765 --> 00:05:50.809
But unless it comes from here...

117
00:05:50.892 --> 00:05:51.893
Yeah.

118
00:05:51.977 --> 00:05:53.353
...the taste is totally different.

119
00:05:53.436 --> 00:05:55.230
The taste. the soil. the climate.

120
00:05:55.313 --> 00:05:57.357
I'm glad you like it.

121
00:05:57.440 --> 00:05:59.276
Most people
don't put oregano on it.

122
00:05:59.359 --> 00:06:01.987
No. This is a typical Sicilian recipe.

123
00:06:02.070 --> 00:06:05.031
So. we-- we try to utilize
all what we have in the farm.

124
00:06:05.115 --> 00:06:06.908
I love it with the oregano.

125
00:06:06.992 --> 00:06:09.452
It's a good food.
and it tells a lot

126
00:06:09.536 --> 00:06:12.080
about the traditional food of Sicily.

127
00:06:12.163 --> 00:06:16.668
So. tell me. do you ever
worry about Etna. um...

128
00:06:19.963 --> 00:06:21.131
We live with it.

129
00:06:22.132 --> 00:06:23.842
Etna is very important for us.

130
00:06:24.301 --> 00:06:26.261
It's a symbol. perhaps.

131
00:06:26.344 --> 00:06:27.178
<i>Si.</i>

132
00:06:27.262 --> 00:06:29.347
It's the mother of the
territory of Catania.

133
00:06:30.432 --> 00:06:32.684
Because you look at it and see...

134
00:06:32.767 --> 00:06:36.396
if you've been away.
and you want to come back.

135
00:06:36.479 --> 00:06:38.189
that is the first thing you see

136
00:06:38.273 --> 00:06:42.152
and then you're back home
in your motherland.

137
00:06:42.235 --> 00:06:44.279
-Yeah. Again. cheers. Cheers.
-Cheers. Thank you.

138
00:06:44.362 --> 00:06:46.907
<i>Grazie. grazie. grazie.</i>

139
00:06:48.825 --> 00:06:51.578
<i>These days. citrus fruit and Sicily</i>

140
00:06:51.661 --> 00:06:54.789
<i>have become almost synonymous.</i>
<i>but the truth is.</i>

141
00:06:54.873 --> 00:06:57.334
<i>oranges aren't native to this island.</i>

142
00:06:58.460 --> 00:06:59.669
<i>It was the Arabs that</i>

143
00:06:59.753 --> 00:07:01.630
<i>introduced citrus here</i>
<i>in the 10th century.</i>

144
00:07:01.713 --> 00:07:03.757
<i>just one of the many foreign cultures</i>

145
00:07:03.840 --> 00:07:07.052
<i>that have brought new ideas</i>
<i>and ingredients to the region.</i>

146
00:07:08.762 --> 00:07:11.514
There's a book about Sicily.

147
00:07:11.598 --> 00:07:15.393
I think it's called <i>The Island</i>
<i>at the Crossroads of History.</i>

148
00:07:15.477 --> 00:07:18.813
and it just talks about how it is.
like. so perfectly situated.

149
00:07:19.856 --> 00:07:23.318
like Italy itself. but actually.
it is the first place

150
00:07:23.401 --> 00:07:25.153
that everybody went to.

151
00:07:33.411 --> 00:07:35.372
<i>This made its capital. Palermo.</i>

152
00:07:35.455 --> 00:07:38.333
<i>one of the most conquered cities on Earth.</i>

153
00:07:42.879 --> 00:07:46.132
<i>While the towns in the east</i>
<i>look and feel Italian.</i>

154
00:07:46.216 --> 00:07:48.593
<i>in contrast. the capital in the west.</i>

155
00:07:48.677 --> 00:07:50.762
<i>has a more layered identity.</i>

156
00:07:52.097 --> 00:07:54.766
<i>Greeks. North Africans. and the Spanish</i>

157
00:07:54.849 --> 00:07:57.102
<i>all made it their home away from home.</i>

158
00:07:57.185 --> 00:07:59.854
<i>And to this day.</i>
<i>the city is a vibrant mosaic</i>

159
00:07:59.938 --> 00:08:02.107
<i>of disparate cultures and ways of living.</i>

160
00:08:06.236 --> 00:08:09.072
So. this is the cathedral of Palermo.

161
00:08:09.155 --> 00:08:11.866
It is a perfect example

162
00:08:11.950 --> 00:08:14.869
of how all these different cultures.

163
00:08:14.953 --> 00:08:18.748
uh. formed the city in a--
a single piece of architecture.

164
00:08:19.624 --> 00:08:24.003
You have Norman. Byzantine. and Arabic.

165
00:08:24.087 --> 00:08:25.588
because this was a mosque.

166
00:08:26.923 --> 00:08:29.634
It's just one of the most
incredible pieces of

167
00:08:29.718 --> 00:08:31.261
architecture...

168
00:08:32.011 --> 00:08:34.639
not only in Sicily.
but in the world. I think.

169
00:08:36.057 --> 00:08:40.061
<i>It's a surprisingly harmonious</i>
<i>blend of historical influences.</i>

170
00:08:40.979 --> 00:08:43.606
<i>Something not only found</i>
<i>in the city's architecture.</i>

171
00:08:43.690 --> 00:08:45.567
<i>but also in its cuisine.</i>

172
00:08:54.492 --> 00:08:58.204
<i>This is the Capo.</i>
<i>a maze-like food market</i>

173
00:08:58.288 --> 00:09:00.623
<i>in an ancient part of Palermo.</i>

174
00:09:02.250 --> 00:09:04.711
<i>Cultures from all over the Mediterranean</i>

175
00:09:04.794 --> 00:09:07.297
<i>have convened here. sharing ingredients...</i>

176
00:09:09.340 --> 00:09:13.303
<i>recipes. and bartering in this market</i>

177
00:09:13.386 --> 00:09:15.180
<i>for over 1.000 years.</i>

178
00:09:15.305 --> 00:09:18.266
- Can I please have 100 grams of these?
- Yes.

179
00:09:18.349 --> 00:09:19.684
Thank you very much.

180
00:09:19.768 --> 00:09:22.604
<i>Local historian</i>
<i>Chiara D'Agostino</i>

181
00:09:22.687 --> 00:09:25.440
<i>is guiding me through</i>
<i>the stalls to sample something</i>

182
00:09:25.523 --> 00:09:28.693
<i>the city has become famous for.</i>
<i>street food.</i>

183
00:09:30.820 --> 00:09:32.363
I'm getting quite hungry.

184
00:09:32.447 --> 00:09:33.573
- so we might as well--
- Yeah. I'm starving.

185
00:09:33.656 --> 00:09:35.450
You know I'm-- please. I'm always hungry.

186
00:09:35.533 --> 00:09:36.534
-Hello.
<i>-Buongiorno.</i>

187
00:09:36.618 --> 00:09:38.995
- Good morning.
- Welcome.

188
00:09:39.662 --> 00:09:43.625
<i>Dainotti's has a reputation</i>
<i>for some of the best snacks in the market.</i>

189
00:09:44.667 --> 00:09:46.336
What's the names of these ones?

190
00:09:46.419 --> 00:09:48.505
These ones. in Palermitano.
are called "cazzilli".

191
00:09:48.588 --> 00:09:49.589
Called what?

192
00:09:49.672 --> 00:09:51.257
- "Cazzilli".
- "Cazzilli"?

193
00:09:51.341 --> 00:09:52.550
It's Palermitano. yes.

194
00:09:52.634 --> 00:09:53.927
<i>-Si.</i>
-Yeah.

195
00:09:54.010 --> 00:09:55.136
The "cazzilli".

196
00:09:55.220 --> 00:09:56.429
-What does it mean?
-You know what it means.

197
00:09:56.513 --> 00:09:58.098
Oh. does it? Okay. alright. okay.

198
00:09:58.181 --> 00:10:00.558
Little penises.

199
00:10:00.975 --> 00:10:04.020
<i>But the pinnacle</i>
<i>of Sicilian street food</i>

200
00:10:04.104 --> 00:10:07.315
<i>is a very special. humble ball of rice.</i>

201
00:10:08.983 --> 00:10:10.819
-We can have <i>arancina.</i>
<i>-Arancino.</i>

202
00:10:10.902 --> 00:10:12.278
-Yeah? <i>Arancina?</i>
-Yeah. yeah. yeah. yeah.

203
00:10:12.362 --> 00:10:13.363
"Arancin-A."

204
00:10:13.446 --> 00:10:14.656
"Arancina". my bad.

205
00:10:14.739 --> 00:10:16.366
"Arancin-a"!

206
00:10:16.449 --> 00:10:21.454
It's very important. in Palermo.
the <i>arancina </i>is female.

207
00:10:21.538 --> 00:10:23.373
-Yes.
-And we care about that.

208
00:10:23.456 --> 00:10:24.999
-Yes.
-In Catania

209
00:10:25.083 --> 00:10:27.335
and east of Sicily. it's male.

210
00:10:27.418 --> 00:10:29.504
-It's male.
<i>-Arancino.</i>

211
00:10:29.587 --> 00:10:30.713
-Why?
-They are different.

212
00:10:30.797 --> 00:10:32.132
Are they different?

213
00:10:32.257 --> 00:10:34.092
Our "arancina" is Arabic.

214
00:10:34.175 --> 00:10:35.009
Yes.

215
00:10:35.093 --> 00:10:38.054
Whereas in Catania it was
brought by the Spanish.

216
00:10:38.138 --> 00:10:39.681
The Aragonese.

217
00:10:39.764 --> 00:10:42.433
They're two completely different recipes.

218
00:10:42.517 --> 00:10:43.393
-Yes. it's true.
-Ah.

219
00:10:43.476 --> 00:10:46.104
Our one is Arabic. a lot of influences.

220
00:10:46.187 --> 00:10:47.772
-It's got saffron in the rice.
-Right. right.

221
00:10:47.856 --> 00:10:50.817
While the one in the east.
in Sicily. is white rice.

222
00:10:50.900 --> 00:10:51.985
- Oh. it is? Okay.
- Yes.

223
00:10:52.068 --> 00:10:53.820
And the fillings as well are different.

224
00:10:53.903 --> 00:10:55.613
Uh. so what's a filling here?

225
00:10:55.697 --> 00:10:58.616
With butter. with meat.
and with meat and mozzarella.

226
00:10:59.325 --> 00:11:00.827
I think I'll have the carne.

227
00:11:02.662 --> 00:11:04.122
- It's beautiful.
- Yes.

228
00:11:04.205 --> 00:11:05.748
- It is beautiful.
- Round. Perfect.

229
00:11:05.832 --> 00:11:07.792
Just one of my favorite things
in the world. yes.

230
00:11:07.876 --> 00:11:10.753
Yes. and also. I-- I wanna try
one of the little penises.

231
00:11:10.837 --> 00:11:12.672
- Yes. okay.
- Yeah.

232
00:11:14.424 --> 00:11:16.134
My grandmother used to make these.

233
00:11:16.217 --> 00:11:18.344
-Mm!
