470
00:21:57.566 --> 00:21:59.777
Does that make any sense?
Anyway. I'm going in.

471
00:21:59.860 --> 00:22:00.861
You'll-- you'll see.

472
00:22:05.491 --> 00:22:08.828
<i>Confusing or not. Trapani seafood couscous</i>

473
00:22:08.911 --> 00:22:11.872
<i>is a dish people now travel</i>
<i>from far and wide to try.</i>

474
00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:18.420
<i>Hajer Aissi. who runs</i>
<i>this traditional trattoria.</i>

475
00:22:18.504 --> 00:22:20.422
<i>makes one of the finest in town.</i>

476
00:22:20.506 --> 00:22:22.132
-Hello. Hello.
-Hello.

477
00:22:22.216 --> 00:22:23.217
Good morning.

478
00:22:23.300 --> 00:22:24.301
Stanley. <i>buongiorno.</i>

479
00:22:24.385 --> 00:22:25.594
Good morning.

480
00:22:28.055 --> 00:22:31.725
<i>Hajer came to Sicily</i>
<i>from Tunisia at the age of six.</i>

481
00:22:32.434 --> 00:22:35.479
Why did your parents come here?

482
00:22:35.563 --> 00:22:39.942
My parents... my dad came first.

483
00:22:40.025 --> 00:22:41.193
Yeah?

484
00:22:41.277 --> 00:22:43.529
He was supposed to stay

485
00:22:43.612 --> 00:22:45.990
a short time. just for work.

486
00:22:46.198 --> 00:22:48.367
He was a carpenter in Tunisia.

487
00:22:48.450 --> 00:22:53.122
Instead. six months to a year
turned into 35 years.

488
00:22:53.205 --> 00:22:54.206
<i>Si?</i>

489
00:22:54.290 --> 00:22:55.291
We've been here 35 years.

490
00:22:55.374 --> 00:22:56.208
-Wow. Wow.
<i>-Si. si. si.</i>

491
00:22:57.877 --> 00:23:00.462
<i>Here. the couscous</i>
<i>is hand-rolled.</i>

492
00:23:00.546 --> 00:23:02.298
<i>It's a lengthy process that involves</i>

493
00:23:02.381 --> 00:23:04.675
<i>gradually adding water to semolina.</i>

494
00:23:05.885 --> 00:23:07.303
What do we do now?

495
00:23:07.386 --> 00:23:09.930
We season it with cinnamon.

496
00:23:10.014 --> 00:23:11.974
onion

497
00:23:12.182 --> 00:23:14.143
and parsley.

498
00:23:14.226 --> 00:23:18.606
Are all these things
in the Tunisian recipe?

499
00:23:18.689 --> 00:23:20.941
No. this is the Trapani recipe.

500
00:23:21.025 --> 00:23:25.321
They had to personalize it. I'd say.

501
00:23:25.404 --> 00:23:26.405
Ah.

502
00:23:26.488 --> 00:23:29.617
- Now it is Sicilian.
- Yes.

503
00:23:32.870 --> 00:23:35.748
<i>The couscous is sealed</i>
<i>using a basic dough</i>

504
00:23:35.831 --> 00:23:38.959
<i>made of flour and water.</i>
<i>then steamed in a couscousier.</i>

505
00:23:40.002 --> 00:23:41.462
Beautiful.

506
00:23:42.922 --> 00:23:44.006
What's next?

507
00:23:44.089 --> 00:23:45.799
The next step is the soup.

508
00:23:45.883 --> 00:23:46.717
<i>Zuppa. </i>

509
00:23:46.800 --> 00:23:49.345
<i>The seafood broth which brings it to life.</i>

510
00:23:49.428 --> 00:23:51.513
<i>is also cooked from scratch.</i>

511
00:23:51.597 --> 00:23:53.724
<i>using the freshest fish from local boats.</i>

512
00:23:54.558 --> 00:23:56.352
This fish. Can you see the fish?

513
00:23:56.435 --> 00:23:58.103
Can you see it? You can speak to me.

514
00:23:58.187 --> 00:24:00.606
- I can see the fish.
- Okay.

515
00:24:00.689 --> 00:24:03.233
So. these beautiful little fish.
everything's fresh today.

516
00:24:03.317 --> 00:24:05.152
These beautiful little fish
are gonna go in. they're gonna

517
00:24:05.235 --> 00:24:07.279
get ground up. and they're gonna
go into the broth.

518
00:24:07.363 --> 00:24:10.824
And then. these bigger fish
are pieces that get cut up later.

519
00:24:10.908 --> 00:24:12.743
I get very excited about fresh fish.

520
00:24:15.621 --> 00:24:17.498
But I want to eat just this.

521
00:24:17.581 --> 00:24:20.376
Right? With some bread.

522
00:24:21.377 --> 00:24:24.922
Then we'll put in
the first part of the fish.

523
00:24:25.005 --> 00:24:27.216
- The "poor" fish.
- "Poor fish"?

524
00:24:27.299 --> 00:24:28.133
<i>Si.</i>

525
00:24:31.720 --> 00:24:35.808
<i>The larger. pricier fish</i>
<i>are then cooked whole in the broth.</i>

526
00:24:36.934 --> 00:24:38.978
Now we moisten the couscous.

527
00:24:39.061 --> 00:24:42.022
And we leave it to sit for two hours.

528
00:24:42.106 --> 00:24:45.734
Otherwise. it swells up in the stomach.

529
00:24:51.407 --> 00:24:52.533
Ooh. Very exciting.

530
00:24:52.616 --> 00:24:54.368
So. what do we do now?

531
00:24:54.451 --> 00:24:56.453
So. now we start.

532
00:24:56.537 --> 00:24:57.371
<i>Si.</i>

533
00:24:57.454 --> 00:25:00.374
We put the broth over it little by little.

534
00:25:00.457 --> 00:25:01.291
<i>Si.</i>

535
00:25:01.375 --> 00:25:04.044
And then slowly.

536
00:25:04.128 --> 00:25:06.964
depending on how much broth you want.

537
00:25:07.047 --> 00:25:08.966
you can add more.

538
00:25:09.049 --> 00:25:10.843
and the couscous is ready.

539
00:25:14.054 --> 00:25:15.389
Mm.

540
00:25:15.472 --> 00:25:16.557
Delicious.

541
00:25:16.640 --> 00:25:18.017
Thank you.

542
00:25:18.434 --> 00:25:19.685
And that...

543
00:25:19.768 --> 00:25:22.604
- How do you say - "cinnamon"?
- Cinnamon. yes.

544
00:25:22.688 --> 00:25:23.731
It's very subtle.

545
00:25:23.814 --> 00:25:24.732
It's delicate.

546
00:25:24.815 --> 00:25:25.816
Yeah.<i> delicato. si.</i>

547
00:25:26.859 --> 00:25:29.611
Now. in Trapani. what's it like...

548
00:25:29.695 --> 00:25:34.199
between Tunisians and Sicilians?

549
00:25:34.283 --> 00:25:36.785
- They're the same.
- The same?

550
00:25:36.869 --> 00:25:39.955
The culture is the same.

551
00:25:40.039 --> 00:25:43.917
At least. I've always considered
it to be the same.

552
00:25:44.001 --> 00:25:48.338
Their customs. flavors too. aromas...

553
00:25:48.422 --> 00:25:53.260
Sicily resembles North Africa a lot.

554
00:25:53.343 --> 00:25:56.180
- They don't live separately?
- No.

555
00:25:56.263 --> 00:25:59.933
The religion is different.
the culture too.

556
00:26:00.017 --> 00:26:04.730
But over the years. little by little.

557
00:26:04.813 --> 00:26:10.152
a cultural maturity has
happened. you could say.

558
00:26:10.235 --> 00:26:13.155
They see the person...

559
00:26:13.238 --> 00:26:15.199
They see beyond. they see the person.

560
00:26:15.282 --> 00:26:18.660
- The person. not the idea.
- Not the context. exactly.

561
00:26:19.912 --> 00:26:22.623
Because really. there is no difference.

562
00:26:23.332 --> 00:26:25.417
<i>-Grazie. </i>Thank you.
<i>-Prego.</i>

563
00:26:26.502 --> 00:26:30.339
<i>Centuries of exchange</i>
<i>between two seemingly different cultures</i>

564
00:26:30.422 --> 00:26:32.883
<i>has enriched Sicilian cuisine</i>
<i>with new dishes</i>

565
00:26:32.966 --> 00:26:34.802
<i>that no matter what one's heritage.</i>

566
00:26:34.885 --> 00:26:37.471
<i>all can agree are delicious.</i>

567
00:26:37.554 --> 00:26:39.723
<i>whether they are made</i>
<i>from the bounty of the sea</i>

568
00:26:39.807 --> 00:26:42.976
<i>or from where I'm headed next.</i>
<i>the mountains.</i>

569
00:26:46.480 --> 00:26:47.856
<i>Up in the rugged north.</i>

570
00:26:47.940 --> 00:26:50.234
<i>the Nebrodi mountains are pig country.</i>

571
00:26:53.612 --> 00:26:56.240
<i>They're home to the Sicilian </i>suino nero...

572
00:26:57.491 --> 00:26:58.784
<i>or black pig.</i>

573
00:27:00.911 --> 00:27:02.788
<i>An ancient native breed.</i>

574
00:27:04.289 --> 00:27:07.417
They've been here since 700 BC.

575
00:27:08.335 --> 00:27:10.879
It has survived for so long

576
00:27:10.963 --> 00:27:13.465
because it adapts to everything.

577
00:27:15.259 --> 00:27:17.344
<i>This is a very unusual pig farm.</i>

578
00:27:19.388 --> 00:27:23.559
<i>It's a world away from the concrete sprawl</i>
<i>of industrialized agriculture.</i>

579
00:27:23.642 --> 00:27:27.229
<i>which unfortunately is more</i>
<i>common in Italy nowadays.</i>

580
00:27:28.230 --> 00:27:30.440
<i>I'm here with farmer Franco Borello.</i>

581
00:27:31.358 --> 00:27:33.986
They eat what they
come across in the woods.

582
00:27:34.069 --> 00:27:38.198
Grasses. roots. acorns.
chestnuts. hazelnuts too.

583
00:27:39.074 --> 00:27:42.786
When they don't find much around.
they come looking for me.

584
00:27:45.038 --> 00:27:46.331
Let's give them some barley.

585
00:27:48.959 --> 00:27:52.129
<i>The Nebrodi</i>
<i>are descended from wild boar.</i>

586
00:27:52.212 --> 00:27:54.214
They're so civilized. in a line.

587
00:27:55.132 --> 00:27:57.843
<i>Over time. they've been</i>
<i>replaced by larger breeds</i>

588
00:27:57.926 --> 00:28:00.429
<i>that yield more meat and make more profit.</i>

589
00:28:02.055 --> 00:28:05.350
But. before. they were almost extinct.

590
00:28:05.434 --> 00:28:07.060
- But. before. they were almost extinct.
-They were almost extinct because...

591
00:28:07.144 --> 00:28:09.396
these were the pigs found in the area.

592
00:28:09.479 --> 00:28:13.775
and all families. here in the
countryside. raised these black pigs.

593
00:28:13.859 --> 00:28:17.154
But then. slowly.
as the countryside was abandoned.

594
00:28:17.237 --> 00:28:19.615
these pigs disappeared.

595
00:28:19.990 --> 00:28:22.618
In the '50s. they were almost gone.

596
00:28:23.160 --> 00:28:26.163
Back then people wanted
lean meat. pink meat.

597
00:28:28.165 --> 00:28:29.791
They wanted a good yield.

598
00:28:30.083 --> 00:28:33.086
They didn't consider
the quality of the meat.

599
00:28:33.170 --> 00:28:34.630
This one has a lot of fat

600
00:28:34.713 --> 00:28:37.007
and now we know it's good for you.

601
00:28:37.090 --> 00:28:38.550
It's a good fat.

602
00:28:38.634 --> 00:28:40.510
With Omega-3.

603
00:28:40.594 --> 00:28:45.265
Eating the fat of these pigs is
like eating extra virgin olive oil.

604
00:28:45.349 --> 00:28:46.850
Yeah.

605
00:28:46.934 --> 00:28:50.687
Let's send them out into the woods.

606
00:28:53.732 --> 00:28:55.484
- They aren't coming?
- They aren't coming.

607
00:29:00.322 --> 00:29:02.658
To make them come over.
I'll give them a little something.

608
00:29:02.741 --> 00:29:04.701
Well. the pigs
were supposed to go out.

609
00:29:04.785 --> 00:29:06.703
but the feed got spilled.

610
00:29:06.787 --> 00:29:08.413
and now they won't leave.

611
00:29:08.497 --> 00:29:11.375
I love that. It's funny.

612
00:29:12.876 --> 00:29:15.045
<i>The pigs clearly just do</i>
<i>their own thing here.</i>

613
00:29:16.755 --> 00:29:19.424
<i>But Franco does intervene</i>
<i>at one time in their lives...</i>

614
00:29:20.425 --> 00:29:21.843
<i>right at the start.</i>

615
00:29:22.719 --> 00:29:25.722
<i>These igloo-like structures. called </i>Zimma.

616
00:29:25.806 --> 00:29:28.433
<i>have been used to shelter</i>
<i>birthing pigs for centuries.</i>

617
00:29:31.228 --> 00:29:33.230
In here is where the piglets are born.

618
00:29:33.814 --> 00:29:35.273
Do you know what this little step is for?

619
00:29:35.357 --> 00:29:36.191
No.

620
00:29:36.274 --> 00:29:38.986
In the first week. it stops
the piglets from getting out.

621
00:29:39.528 --> 00:29:41.446
Because we're in the woods.

622
00:29:41.530 --> 00:29:45.409
there are falcons that could
get them in those first days.

623
00:29:45.492 --> 00:29:48.161
After a week. they're bigger.

624
00:29:48.245 --> 00:29:50.330
so birds of prey can't get them.

625
00:29:50.706 --> 00:29:53.625
It's not damp.
It's a perfect habitat.

626
00:29:53.709 --> 00:29:54.710
Wow.

627
00:29:54.793 --> 00:29:57.004
Do you want to go in?

628
00:29:57.087 --> 00:29:57.921
-No. it's okay.
<i>-No. bene.</i>

629
00:30:00.966 --> 00:30:04.344
<i>But the family farm</i>
<i>also boasts a family restaurant.</i>

630
00:30:04.428 --> 00:30:07.055
<i>which. though remote. pulls in diners</i>

631
00:30:07.139 --> 00:30:08.557
<i>from all over the island.</i>

632
00:30:11.101 --> 00:30:15.147
<i>Talented young chef Alessandro Maniaci</i>
<i>runs the kitchen.</i>

633
00:30:17.607 --> 00:30:18.817
Hello?

634
00:30:18.900 --> 00:30:19.901
Good morning.

635
00:30:19.985 --> 00:30:20.986
- Hi.
- Hi.

636
00:30:21.069 --> 00:30:22.571
<i>The home cooking touch</i>

637
00:30:22.654 --> 00:30:24.656
<i>comes from Franco's mother Anna.</i>

638
00:30:24.740 --> 00:30:26.074
Hi.

639
00:30:26.158 --> 00:30:27.451
Good morning.

640
00:30:27.534 --> 00:30:31.329
<i>At 87. she still cooks dishes</i>
<i>for the restaurant daily.</i>

641
00:30:31.413 --> 00:30:32.706
When was this made?

642
00:30:32.789 --> 00:30:35.000
This is very fresh.
it was made two days ago.

643
00:30:35.083 --> 00:30:38.253
It's different from the pork
we eat every day.

644
00:30:38.336 --> 00:30:39.337
<i>Si. si.</i>

645
00:30:39.421 --> 00:30:42.215
-The meat is so dark.
-Yes.

646
00:30:42.299 --> 00:30:44.843
That's really because of the pigs' diet.

647
00:30:44.926 --> 00:30:46.970
They are free range.

648
00:30:47.054 --> 00:30:48.388
They're free.

649
00:30:48.472 --> 00:30:51.058
<i>-Si. </i>And then. what's this?
-Gelatina.

650
00:30:51.141 --> 00:30:52.851
This is the head of the pig.

651
00:30:52.934 --> 00:30:54.436
- Mm-hmm?
- And like all the...

652
00:30:54.519 --> 00:30:56.938
The parts which are considered
the scraps of the pig.

653
00:30:57.022 --> 00:30:58.690
This represent our philosophy.

654
00:30:58.774 --> 00:30:59.900
-Yeah.
-Don't throw away nothing.

655
00:30:59.983 --> 00:31:01.068
-Yeah.
-From nose to tail.

656
00:31:01.151 --> 00:31:02.360
-Nose to tail.
-Yes.

657
00:31:02.444 --> 00:31:03.487
-Nose to tail. yeah.
-Nose to tail.

658
00:31:03.570 --> 00:31:05.072
-This is the international...
-Yes.

659
00:31:05.155 --> 00:31:06.698
-...gesture for nose to tail.
-Nose to tail. nose to tail.

660
00:31:07.449 --> 00:31:09.785
We're making fried sausage

661
00:31:09.868 --> 00:31:12.621
with eggs and broccoli.

662
00:31:12.704 --> 00:31:16.625
Broccoli? And it's your broccoli?

663
00:31:17.167 --> 00:31:20.504
Yes. from our farm. We grew it.

664
00:31:22.506 --> 00:31:24.299
Tell him the origins of the dish. Grandma.

665
00:31:24.382 --> 00:31:25.717
Where does it come from?

666
00:31:26.384 --> 00:31:32.182
When priests used to
go to the countryside...

667
00:31:33.433 --> 00:31:34.851
to bless the houses.

668
00:31:35.310 --> 00:31:39.272
They don't do it anymore.
You know. there's no time.

669
00:31:39.356 --> 00:31:40.649
Even priests don't have the time.

670
00:31:40.732 --> 00:31:41.650
<i>Si. Si.</i>

671
00:31:42.943 --> 00:31:47.781
So. this lady wanted to give
the priest something.

672
00:31:47.864 --> 00:31:53.036
She said. "What shall I give you?
Some eggs from our hens?

673
00:31:53.120 --> 00:31:58.375
Or would you rather some
sausage from our pig?"

674
00:31:58.875 --> 00:32:03.421
And the priest said. "Mmm.
I like both fried sausage AND eggs."

675
00:32:05.590 --> 00:32:07.759
And that's the priest's morsel.

676
00:32:07.843 --> 00:32:09.511
Yeah.

677
00:32:11.263 --> 00:32:12.848
<i>Everything cooked and served</i>

678
00:32:12.931 --> 00:32:16.143
<i>is sourced from the farm itself</i>
<i>or the local area.</i>

679
00:32:18.603 --> 00:32:21.189
Oh. my God. the smell of it though.

680
00:32:24.609 --> 00:32:27.904
<i>Franco's daughter Anna Laura</i>
<i>and son Giuseppe</i>

681
00:32:27.988 --> 00:32:30.073
<i>are also involved in running the business.</i>

682
00:32:31.783 --> 00:32:32.784
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

683
00:32:34.119 --> 00:32:35.162
Thank you. Grandma.

684
00:32:35.245 --> 00:32:36.538
<i>-Grazie.</i>
-Thank you. thank you.

685
00:32:38.123 --> 00:32:39.457
So...

686
00:32:39.541 --> 00:32:41.835
I love it. but I would like to
try that one.

687
00:32:42.294 --> 00:32:45.046
- Grandma's dish.
- This is a dream.

688
00:32:45.130 --> 00:32:46.131
<i>Si.</i>

689
00:32:47.674 --> 00:32:50.302
That is just so beautiful.

690
00:32:50.385 --> 00:32:51.887
I have to taste it.

691
00:32:55.515 --> 00:32:57.017
That's delicious.

692
00:32:57.100 --> 00:32:58.101
Eggs.

693
00:32:59.561 --> 00:33:01.730
The sausage. the broccolini.

694
00:33:03.315 --> 00:33:05.567
Perfect. I will make this
as soon as I come back home.

695
00:33:05.650 --> 00:33:06.484
You can bring it in England. Yes.

696
00:33:07.402 --> 00:33:09.529
You have not tried prosciutto yet.

697
00:33:09.613 --> 00:33:10.697
<i>Oh. si.</i>

698
00:33:10.780 --> 00:33:11.740
Thank you.

699
00:33:14.075 --> 00:33:17.662
Oh. my God. Oh. my God. that fat.

700
00:33:17.746 --> 00:33:20.624
-The fat is so smooth.
-It's so interesting.

701
00:33:21.374 --> 00:33:24.002
Well. I'm never leaving. <i>Si. grazie.</i>

702
00:33:28.548 --> 00:33:30.800
<i>Grazie.</i>

703
00:33:37.224 --> 00:33:39.142
Big farms.

704
00:33:39.226 --> 00:33:41.895
is it difficult to fight them?

705
00:33:42.520 --> 00:33:44.439
Big companies are absorbing
almost everything.

706
00:33:44.522 --> 00:33:45.523
<i>Si.</i>

707
00:33:45.607 --> 00:33:47.067
Almost everything.
It is a pity.

708
00:33:47.150 --> 00:33:51.238
Traditions get lost.
the land is abandoned.

709
00:33:51.780 --> 00:33:55.325
To safeguard the land.
we need small companies.

710
00:33:55.408 --> 00:33:57.452
Export?

711
00:33:58.078 --> 00:33:59.120
No.

712
00:33:59.204 --> 00:34:00.997
Export...

713
00:34:01.331 --> 00:34:03.250
I am not that interested in exporting.

714
00:34:04.417 --> 00:34:06.670
I could export. I have many.
many requests.

715
00:34:06.753 --> 00:34:09.923
However. I would need
to increase production.

716
00:34:10.006 --> 00:34:15.637
It would become a farming system
of intensive production.

717
00:34:16.012 --> 00:34:17.389
And this is not good.

718
00:34:17.472 --> 00:34:21.017
We raise the right number of animals

719
00:34:22.227 --> 00:34:24.813
for the land
that we have available.

720
00:34:25.313 --> 00:34:27.482
Yeah. Well. thank you.

721
00:34:27.565 --> 00:34:28.984
Thank you for everything.

722
00:34:29.067 --> 00:34:30.277
Really.

723
00:34:30.360 --> 00:34:31.486
Thank you.

724
00:34:31.569 --> 00:34:32.529
Thank you so much.

725
00:34:32.862 --> 00:34:33.905
Grandma.

726
00:34:35.657 --> 00:34:36.658
This was...

727
00:34:37.951 --> 00:34:39.119
marvelous.

728
00:34:42.914 --> 00:34:45.292
<i>The refusal</i>
<i>of the Borello family</i>

729
00:34:45.375 --> 00:34:48.003
<i>to compromise their agricultural practices</i>

730
00:34:48.086 --> 00:34:50.588
<i>and bring food as good</i>
<i>as this to the table</i>

731
00:34:50.672 --> 00:34:52.966
<i>makes them a very rare breed themselves</i>

732
00:34:53.049 --> 00:34:54.884
<i>in a quickly changing world.</i>

733
00:34:56.428 --> 00:34:59.556
<i>My final stop is an equally idyllic place.</i>

734
00:34:59.639 --> 00:35:02.267
<i>that is facing yet</i>
<i>another man-made threat.</i>

735
00:35:16.656 --> 00:35:18.825
It seems that the Greeks were here.

736
00:35:28.835 --> 00:35:31.296
<i>This is the Valley of the Temples.</i>

737
00:35:31.379 --> 00:35:35.258
<i>five square miles of ancient</i>
<i>Greek archaeological treasures</i>

738
00:35:35.342 --> 00:35:37.427
<i>close to the southern coast of the island.</i>

739
00:35:39.304 --> 00:35:43.350
<i>Alongside the ruins is a huge garden.</i>
<i>known as Kolymbethra.</i>

740
00:35:46.019 --> 00:35:48.104
<i>It's a horticultural treasure chest.</i>

741
00:35:50.315 --> 00:35:53.360
Here. we got
1.500 plants you know?

742
00:35:53.443 --> 00:35:56.821
This is the perfect example
of a Mediterranean garden.

743
00:35:58.156 --> 00:36:00.283
<i>Federica Salvo is its director.</i>

744
00:36:01.910 --> 00:36:04.371
<i>We got 16 different kind of oranges.</i>

745
00:36:05.372 --> 00:36:08.375
<i>Along the walls.</i>
<i>you can see prickly pears.</i>

746
00:36:08.458 --> 00:36:10.585
- <i>Yeah.</i>
<i>- They grow everywhere.</i>

747
00:36:10.669 --> 00:36:15.215
<i>We got. of course.</i>
<i>olive trees. carob. and almond.</i>

748
00:36:17.092 --> 00:36:19.928
<i>This valley wasn't always so fertile.</i>

749
00:36:20.011 --> 00:36:21.888
<i>When the Greeks arrived. it was barren.</i>

750
00:36:23.973 --> 00:36:25.809
<i>But not for long.</i>

751
00:36:25.892 --> 00:36:30.522
Kolymbethra is a Greek word
which means. uh. "holy pool."

752
00:36:30.605 --> 00:36:35.402
The idea of the Greeks
was to convert this quarry

753
00:36:35.485 --> 00:36:39.572
into a huge artificial. uh. water basin.

754
00:36:40.407 --> 00:36:44.035
2.500 years ago.
there were 18 aqueducts...

755
00:36:44.953 --> 00:36:48.164
dug into the stone
which were pouring water

756
00:36:48.248 --> 00:36:49.791
inside this huge water basin.

757
00:36:49.874 --> 00:36:51.668
The water coming in here...

758
00:36:51.751 --> 00:36:53.044
-Yes.
-...you still have...

759
00:36:54.003 --> 00:36:56.089
-the original structures?
-Absolutely.

760
00:36:56.756 --> 00:37:00.009
Thanks to this.
we can irrigate our garden.

761
00:37:01.010 --> 00:37:03.555
That's why it's so lush and green.

762
00:37:06.558 --> 00:37:08.560
<i>Kolymbethra is like a paradise.</i>

763
00:37:08.643 --> 00:37:10.979
<i>but it's under threat from climate change.</i>

764
00:37:11.062 --> 00:37:12.939
<i>The hottest temperature</i>
<i>ever recorded in Europe</i>

765
00:37:13.022 --> 00:37:14.899
<i>was right here in Sicily.</i>

766
00:37:14.983 --> 00:37:17.444
<i>a scorching 120 degrees Fahrenheit.</i>

767
00:37:17.527 --> 00:37:20.613
<i>which is a concern for Federica</i>
<i>and her colleagues.</i>

768
00:37:23.158 --> 00:37:24.242
<i>Ciao.</i>

769
00:37:24.325 --> 00:37:25.577
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

770
00:37:25.660 --> 00:37:26.828
Stanley.

771
00:37:26.911 --> 00:37:28.747
<i>Rino Frenda is keeping a close eye</i>

772
00:37:28.830 --> 00:37:29.914
<i>on the almond trees.</i>

773
00:37:29.998 --> 00:37:30.999
<i>Ciao.</i>

774
00:37:31.082 --> 00:37:34.210
Are you trimming the dry ends?

775
00:37:34.294 --> 00:37:38.089
Every year we do
what we call pruning.

776
00:37:38.173 --> 00:37:41.176
which is used to give
a shape to the plant.

777
00:37:41.259 --> 00:37:43.219
and to let it grow better.

778
00:37:43.303 --> 00:37:45.263
For instance. this bit here.

779
00:37:45.346 --> 00:37:46.890
which I am yet to prune.

780
00:37:46.973 --> 00:37:49.809
but as you can see. there's a dry part

781
00:37:49.893 --> 00:37:52.061
that needs to be removed.

782
00:37:52.145 --> 00:37:54.606
because plants. unlike us.
cannot go to the barber.

783
00:37:54.689 --> 00:37:56.649
So we have to come here instead.

784
00:37:57.317 --> 00:37:58.943
I also don't go to the barber.

785
00:37:59.027 --> 00:38:00.779
- You're lucky.
- I used to. many years ago.

786
00:38:00.862 --> 00:38:01.696
Not anymore.

787
00:38:02.447 --> 00:38:05.950
Why are there no flowers.
at the moment. on this tree?

788
00:38:06.034 --> 00:38:12.749
Because. of course. there have
been changes in temperature and climate.

789
00:38:12.832 --> 00:38:15.043
which have confused the plants.

790
00:38:15.126 --> 00:38:19.088
and so they don't flower uniformly.

791
00:38:19.172 --> 00:38:21.925
<i> It's not just</i>
<i>the trees that are confused.</i>

792
00:38:22.008 --> 00:38:24.093
<i>the native black bees are struggling too.</i>

793
00:38:25.011 --> 00:38:26.721
Of course.
the bees are attracted

794
00:38:26.805 --> 00:38:29.015
by the scent of-- of a flower.

795
00:38:29.098 --> 00:38:31.059
-or-- or a plant in general.
-Mm-hmm.

796
00:38:31.142 --> 00:38:34.896
With warmer springs
or earlier springs.

797
00:38:34.979 --> 00:38:37.649
the scent comes out earlier.

798
00:38:37.732 --> 00:38:40.610
-Earlier.
-So. the bees emerge earlier.

799
00:38:40.693 --> 00:38:41.945
-Yes.
-But sometimes.

800
00:38:42.028 --> 00:38:43.780
there is not enough food for them.

801
00:38:43.863 --> 00:38:45.073
-Ah.
-And they die.

802
00:38:45.156 --> 00:38:47.450
so entire families are disappearing.

803
00:38:48.243 --> 00:38:50.411
You're starting to
plant different kinds of trees.

804
00:38:50.495 --> 00:38:52.247
aren't you. different kinds of fruit?

805
00:38:52.372 --> 00:38:56.835
Actually. some companies in Sicily
have already embarked on this journey.

806
00:38:56.918 --> 00:38:59.420
towards growing tropical fruits.

807
00:38:59.504 --> 00:39:03.716
Some passion fruit. some avocado.

808
00:39:03.800 --> 00:39:09.931
some tried with banana plants.

809
00:39:10.014 --> 00:39:13.142
but these are still preliminary steps.

810
00:39:13.226 --> 00:39:15.812
- It's an experimental phase.
- Yes. it's in the experimental phase.

811
00:39:15.895 --> 00:39:17.355
<i>Si. Si.</i>

812
00:39:19.566 --> 00:39:22.110
<i>Hopefully. these</i>
<i>experiments will work out.</i>

813
00:39:22.193 --> 00:39:24.988
<i>After all. Sicilians are past masters</i>

814
00:39:25.071 --> 00:39:27.490
<i>at making the best of things</i>

815
00:39:27.574 --> 00:39:29.742
<i>and many of them are on the table today.</i>

816
00:39:36.207 --> 00:39:38.710
<i>There's no kitchen here. but no matter.</i>

817
00:39:39.836 --> 00:39:41.713
<i>Alessandro and Giuseppe have come down</i>

818
00:39:41.796 --> 00:39:44.632
<i>from the mountains to cook al fresco.</i>

819
00:39:46.384 --> 00:39:47.760
<i>They're making three different dishes</i>

820
00:39:47.844 --> 00:39:50.305
<i>with some of the island's</i>
<i>extraordinary produce.</i>

821
00:39:52.098 --> 00:39:53.182
-Hello.
-Wow.

822
00:39:53.266 --> 00:39:54.350
-Hello.
-How are you?

823
00:39:54.434 --> 00:39:58.396
This is simply a pasta with sardines.

824
00:39:58.479 --> 00:39:59.772
<i>Grazie.</i>

825
00:40:01.107 --> 00:40:04.402
Pine nuts. raisins. saffron. tomato paste

826
00:40:04.485 --> 00:40:06.321
and. at the end. raw anchovies.

827
00:40:07.155 --> 00:40:07.989
So good.

828
00:40:10.199 --> 00:40:11.534
These...

829
00:40:11.618 --> 00:40:13.119
- Flavors.
- Flavors.

830
00:40:13.202 --> 00:40:14.287
they are...

831
00:40:14.370 --> 00:40:16.497
truly Sicilian?

832
00:40:16.915 --> 00:40:18.333
Flavors. colors... all of it.

833
00:40:18.416 --> 00:40:22.295
We have a lot of examples of dishes.

834
00:40:22.378 --> 00:40:24.005
which are typical of Sicily.

835
00:40:24.088 --> 00:40:28.760
whose ingredients are mostly
not from the region.

836
00:40:29.135 --> 00:40:32.513
but in which the Sicilian genius
was to put them all together in one dish.

837
00:40:32.597 --> 00:40:33.681
Put it all together.

838
00:40:33.765 --> 00:40:34.849
<i>-Si.</i>
<i>-Si.</i>

839
00:40:34.933 --> 00:40:35.975
- So. we're genius. guys.
- Good?

840
00:40:36.059 --> 00:40:37.226
-Yes. genius.
-We didn't know that.

841
00:40:37.310 --> 00:40:38.478
You are geniuses.

842
00:40:38.561 --> 00:40:40.355
They are.

843
00:40:48.571 --> 00:40:49.656
What are we eating here?

844
00:40:49.739 --> 00:40:50.949
Black pig's ribs.

845
00:40:52.116 --> 00:40:55.036
<i>The ribs are finished</i>
<i>with an </i>agrodolce<i> sauce.</i>

846
00:40:55.119 --> 00:40:58.206
<i>made with honey from those</i>
<i>all-important black bees.</i>

847
00:40:59.207 --> 00:41:00.416
- Chef.
- Mm.

848
00:41:00.500 --> 00:41:01.584
You're spoiling us.

849
00:41:01.668 --> 00:41:02.752
Wow.

850
00:41:02.835 --> 00:41:03.836
Thank you.

851
00:41:04.504 --> 00:41:06.547
Can we eat with our hands?

852
00:41:06.631 --> 00:41:07.799
Whatever you want to do.

853
00:41:11.135 --> 00:41:12.136
Wow.

854
00:41:15.390 --> 00:41:17.558
Oh. my God. that's so good!

855
00:41:17.642 --> 00:41:18.810
- Mm.
- That pork.

856
00:41:18.893 --> 00:41:19.936
Very good.

857
00:41:20.311 --> 00:41:22.480
My compliments to those
who raised the pig.

858
00:41:23.773 --> 00:41:28.403
Because working in agriculture
is not easy. especially in Sicily.

859
00:41:28.486 --> 00:41:32.031
But in the morning. when I find
myself surrounded by the almond trees.

860
00:41:32.365 --> 00:41:36.536
I love it. Amongst the dew.
and the smell of flowers.

861
00:41:36.619 --> 00:41:40.790
you walk to an almond tree
that just blossomed.

862
00:41:40.873 --> 00:41:44.502
you smell it - it's like going
into space. trust me.

863
00:41:44.585 --> 00:41:45.670
Let me tell you.

864
00:41:45.753 --> 00:41:47.171
I'm saying this with my heart.

865
00:41:47.255 --> 00:41:48.256
It's true.

866
00:41:53.261 --> 00:41:54.721
- Wow!
- Oh!

867
00:41:54.804 --> 00:41:56.264
Oh. look how beautiful.

868
00:41:57.390 --> 00:41:58.891
What fruits did you use?

869
00:41:59.642 --> 00:42:01.936
The custard is made of blood oranges.

870
00:42:02.020 --> 00:42:03.813
On top we have mangos.

871
00:42:03.896 --> 00:42:04.897
papaya.

872
00:42:04.981 --> 00:42:06.065
passion fruit.

873
00:42:06.149 --> 00:42:07.150
and a bit of avocado too.

874
00:42:07.233 --> 00:42:08.443
which is also a fruit.

875
00:42:08.526 --> 00:42:09.986
- Mm.
- That's delicious.

876
00:42:10.528 --> 00:42:12.155
- Amazing.
- That's amazing.

877
00:42:13.990 --> 00:42:15.658
For me. this is the future.

878
00:42:16.117 --> 00:42:17.827
We already have tradition.

879
00:42:18.161 --> 00:42:22.790
and innovation can be brought by us.
the new generations.

880
00:42:23.249 --> 00:42:27.003
We can give Sicily what it's missing.

881
00:42:27.336 --> 00:42:30.214
a bit of innovation and a bit of vision.

882
00:42:30.298 --> 00:42:31.466
for the future.

883
00:42:31.549 --> 00:42:32.550
<i>Si.</i>

884
00:42:32.633 --> 00:42:33.843
Shall we?

885
00:42:35.178 --> 00:42:37.346
Cheers.

886
00:42:37.430 --> 00:42:39.724
Thank you. chefs. Thank you. thank you.

887
00:42:40.975 --> 00:42:42.685
Thank you. you've been so kind.

888
00:42:48.066 --> 00:42:50.443
<i>Sicily is an island</i>
<i>like no other...</i>

889
00:42:52.278 --> 00:42:54.363
<i>as rich and varied as the many cultures</i>

890
00:42:54.447 --> 00:42:57.075
<i>which have shaped its past and present.</i>

891
00:42:57.158 --> 00:43:00.328
<i>Its ability to absorb so many influences.</i>

892
00:43:00.411 --> 00:43:04.165
<i>yet remain distinctly itself.</i>
<i>is perhaps the key</i>

893
00:43:04.248 --> 00:43:06.000
<i>to its delicious difference.</i>
